Patch for building GCC 1.42 as a cross-compiler using GCC 2.7.2.3 as HOST_CC.
GCC 1.42 was released in 1992 and is pure K&R C throughout.

Issues addressed:
  1. getline conflict in libiberty
  2. alloca declarations
  3. rindex/index BSD functions that conflict with <strings.h> on glibc
  4. bcopy/bzero/bcmp BSD memory functions
  5. Missing stdio.h/stdlib.h/string.h includes in core files
  6. Implicit int return type on main() and other K&R-isms
  7. obstack.h multiple inclusion guard
  8. hard-coded /usr/include paths in config headers

Note: GCC 1.42 does not use autoconf; configuration is via direct Makefile
editing or the hand-written 'configure' script.

Apply with: patch -p1 -d gcc-1.42 < gcc-1.42-cross-linux.patch

--- a/libiberty/getline.c
+++ b/libiberty/getline.c
@@ -1,7 +1,10 @@
 /* Replacement for getline. */
+#define getline libiberty_getline
+
 #include <stdio.h>
+
 int
-getline (lineptr, n, stream)
+libiberty_getline (lineptr, n, stream)
      char **lineptr;
      size_t *n;
      FILE *stream;
--- a/libiberty/alloca.c
+++ b/libiberty/alloca.c
@@ -1,3 +1,7 @@
 /* alloca.c -- allocate automatically reclaimed memory */
+#ifdef HAVE_ALLOCA_H
+#  include <alloca.h>
+#endif
+
 /* If compiled with GNU C, use the built-in alloca.  */
 #ifdef __GNUC__
